{{multiple images | direction = vertical | width = 250 | image1 = SCHEMATIC OF THE DOUBOCHINSKI PENDULUM.png | alt1 = Schematic. | caption1 = Fig.1. Schematics of the Doubochinski’s pendulum | image2 = Doubochinski_pendulum.svg | alt2 = First four quantized amplitudes. | caption2 = Fig.2. First four quantized amplitudes of Doubochinski’s pendulum at a magnetic field frequency f=50Hz. Solenoid is located at the bottom of the pendulum. }} '''Doubochinski’s pendulum''' is a classical oscillator interacting with a high-frequency field in such a way that the oscillator takes on a discrete set of stable regimes of oscillation, each at a frequency near to the proper frequency of the oscillator, but each with a distinct, "quantized" amplitude. <ref name="Vainshtein 1978">{{Cite journal | author = L.A.Vainshtein |author2=Ya.B.Doubochinski | title = On the low-frequency oscillations under the influence of high-frequency force | series = 48 | journal = Zh. Tekh. Fiz [Sov. Phys.-Tech. Phys] | volume = [23] | year = 1978 | pages = 1321 [745] | url = http://www.kapitza.ras.ru/index.php?cont=journ&lang=ru&year=1978 | issue = 1494 }} </ref> <ref name="Doubochinski 1979"> {{Cite journal| author = D.B.Doubochinski |author2=Ya.B.Duboshinsky | journal = Zh. Tech. Fiz [Sov. Phys.-Tech. Phys]| series = 49 | title = Discrete modes of a system subject to an inhomogeneous high-frequency force | volume = [24] | year = 1979 | pages = 1160 [642] |display-authors=etal}} </ref> <ref name="Landa 2001">{{Cite book | author = P.S.Landa | title = Nonlinear Oscillations and Waves in Dynamical Systems | publisher = Kluwer Academic Publishers | year = 2001 | url = http://www.gbv.de/dms/goettingen/193719193.pdf | pages = 307 }} </ref> <ref name="Tennenbaum 2005">{{Cite journal | author = J.Tennenbaum | title = Amplitude Quantization as an Elementary Property of Macroscopic. Vibrating Systems | journal = 21st Century Science & Technology | date = Winter 2005 | url = http://www.21stcenturysciencetech.com/2006_articles/Amplitude.W05.pdf }} </ref> <ref name="Weldon 2010">{{Cite journal| author = Weldon J. Wilson | journal = Professor of Engineering and Physics, Weldon Wilson's Home Page | title = Amplitude Quantization as a Fundamental Property of Coupled Oscillator Systems | url = http://cyberphysics.org/wwilson/Talks/CNLS%20Talk%20v3/CNLS%20Talk.ppt | year = 2010 }} </ref> <ref name="Weldon 2012">{{Cite journal |author = Weldon J.Wilson |journal = Professor of Engineering and Physics, Weldon Wilson's Home Page |title = Senior Engineering Design Possible Projects List, 2011-2012 |url = http://cyberphysics.org/wwilson/Courses/SeniorDesign/Resources/PossibleProjectsList11-12.pdf |year = 2012 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} </ref> <ref name="Doubochinski 2013">{{cite conference | url = http://medyna2013.sciencesconf.org/12950/document | title = Theory and applications of the macroscopic quantization effect in nonlinearly-coopled vibrating systems. | author1 = D.B.Doubochinski | author2 = J.Tennenbaum | conference = 1st Euro-Mediterranean Conference on Structural Dynamics and Vibroacoustics | publisher = MEDYNA 2013 | date = 23 April 2013 | location = Marrakech, Morocco }} </ref> The phenomenon of amplitude quantization in this sort of coupled system was first discovered by the brothers Danil and Yakov Doubochinski in 1968&ndash;69.
A simple demonstration apparatus consists of a mechanical pendulum interacting with a magnetic field (Fig. 1). <ref name="Vainshtein 1978"/> <ref name="Doubochinski 1979"/> <ref name="Landa 2001"/> <ref name="Tennenbaum 2005"/> <ref name="Doubochinski 1982">{{Cite journal | author = D.B.Doubochinski |author2=Ya.B.Doubochinski | title = Wave excitation of an oscillator having a discrete series of stable amplitudes | series = 3 | journal = Dokl. Akad. Nauk SSSR [Sov. Phys. Doklady] | volume = [27] | year = 1982 | pages = 605 [564] }} </ref> <ref name="Penner 1973">{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1070/PU1973v016n01ABEH005156| author = D.I.Penner |author2=D.B.Duboshinskii | journal = Soviet Physics Uspekhi | title = Asynchronous excitation of undamped oscillations | url = http://iopscience.iop.org/0038-5670/16/1/A13;jsessionid=0F6175955F28F2EE19CCAA36B1F61DB0.c3 | volume = 16 | issue = 1| pages = 158–160 | year = 1973 | bibcode = 1973SvPhU..16..158P}} </ref> <ref name="Damgov 1986">{{Cite journal | author = V.N.Damgov |author2=D.B.Duboshinskii |author3=Ia.B.Duboshinskii | title = The excitation of undamped oscillations with a discrete series of stable amplitudes | language=Russian | journal=Bolgarskaia Akademiia Nauk, Doklady | volume=39 |issue=9 |pages=47–50 | bibcode = 1986BlDok..39...47D | year = 1986 }} </ref> <ref name="Damgov 1989">{{Cite journal| author = V.Damgov |author2=I.Popov | title = "Discrete" Oscillations and Multiple Attractors in Kick-excited Systems | url = http://downloads.hindawi.com/journals/ddns/2000/985784.pdf | issue = Discrete Dynamics in Nature and Society | pages = 2, 3, 25, 26 | year = 1989 }} </ref> <ref name="Doubochinski 1991">{{Cite journal | author = D.B.Doubochinski |author2=Ya.B.Doubochinski | title = Amorcage argumen-taire d’oscillations entretenues avec une serie discrete d’amplitudes stable | journal = EDF Bulletin de la direction des etudes et recherches, serie C, Mathematiques, Informatique | year = 1991 | pages=11–20}} </ref> <ref name="Beech 2014">{{Cite book | author = Martin Beech | title = The Pendulum Paradigm: Variations on a Theme and the Measure of Heaven and Earth | publisher = Universal Publishers | year = 2014 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=qumVBAAAQBAJ | pages = 290 }} </ref> <ref name="Tournaments 2015">{{cite web |url = http://kit.ilyam.org/SD_2015_IYPT_Reference_kit.pdf |title = Preparation to the Young Physicists’ Tournaments’ 2015 |date = 2014 }} </ref> The system is composed of two interacting oscillatory processes: a pendulum arm with a natural frequency on the order of 0.5&ndash;1&nbsp;Hz, with a small permanent magnet fixed at its moving end; and a stationary electromagnet ([[solenoid]]) positioned under the [[equilibrium point]] of the pendulum’s trajectory and supplied with alternating current of fixed frequency, typically in the range of 10&ndash;1000&nbsp;Hz. The mechanical pendulum arm and solenoid are configured in such a way, that the pendulum arm interacts with the oscillating magnetic field of the solenoid only over a limited portion of its trajectory &ndash; the so-called "zone of interaction" &ndash; outside of which the strength of the magnetic field drops off rapidly to zero. This spatial inhomogeniety of the interaction is key to the quantized behavior and other unusual properties of the system.
When released at any arbitrary starting position, the pendulum’s motion evolves into one of a discrete set of stable oscillation modes, having sharply differing amplitudes, but approximately the same period of oscillation – close to the pendulum’s undisturbed period (Fig. 2). In each such mode, the energy lost by friction in the pendulum’s motion, is compensated by an average net energy transfer from the oscillating magnetic field, in a self-regulating manner. <ref name="Landa 2001"/> <ref name="Tennenbaum 2005"/> <ref name="Weldon 2010"/> <ref name="Damgov 1989"/> <ref name="Doubochinski 1991"/> <ref name="Landa 1989"> {{Cite journal| author = P.S.Landa |author2=Y.B.Duboshinskii | title = Self-oscillatory systems with high-frequency energy sources | url = http://www.turpion.org/php/reference.phtml?journal_id=pu&paper_id=2750&volume=32&issue=8&type=xrf | publisher = Turpion Limited | year = 1989 }} </ref> <ref name="Damgov 1992">{{Cite journal | author = V.N.Damgov |author2=D.B.Douboshinsky | title = The wave nature and dynamical quantization of the solar system | journal = An International Journal of Solar System Science | volume=56 |issue=3 | date = March 1992 | pages = 233–242 | url = https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2FBF00116289 | doi=10.1007/bf00116289 | bibcode=1992EM&P...56..233D}} </ref> <ref name="Doubochinski site">{{Cite web|url=http://www.doubochinski.com|title=Doubochinski’s site|access-date=2018-11-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014223245/http://www.doubochinski.com/#|archive-date=2017-10-14|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> <ref name="Doubochinski 2012">{{cite conference | url = http://phoenix.eng.psu.ac.th/qa/55_55/Component/SupportData/%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%AD%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%AA%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A3%E0%B9%81%E0%B8%99%E0%B8%9A/%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%A4%E0%B8%8A.pdf | title = New Physical Effect Permits Factor-of-Ten Reduction in Energy Requirements for Cooling. | author1 = D.B.Doubochinski | author2 = J.Tennenbaum | year = 2012 | conference = International Conference on Advanced Material and Manufacturing Science | publisher = ICAMMS 2012 | page = M1191 }} </ref> The stability of each amplitude-mode is maintained by a constant self-adjustment of the phase relationship between the pendulum and the high-frequency field. Through its interaction with the field, the pendulum extracts the amount of energy needed to compensate its frictional losses for a given period. The pendulum compensates for the changes in the strength of the magnetic field, <ref name="Beech 2014"/> <ref name="Tournaments 2015"/> <ref name="Doubochinski 2014">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.4028/www.scientific.net/AMR.875-877.1842 | author = Doubochinski Danil B. | author2 = Tennenbaum Jonathan | title = New Physical Effect Permits Factor-of-Ten Reduction in EnergyRequirements for Cooling. | url = http://www.scientific.net/AMR.875-877.1842 | volume = 875–877 | pages = 1842–1846 | year = 2014 | journal = Advanced Materials Research | publisher = Trans Tech Publications, Switzerland }} </ref> <ref name="Doubochinski 2015">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1166/qm.2015.1281 | author = Doubochinski Danil | author2 = Tennenbaum Jonathan | title = A New Dynamical Conception of Physical Objects and Their Interactions. | url = http://www.ingentaconnect.com/contentone/asp/qm/2015/00000004/00000003/art00009 | volume = 4 | issue = 3 | pages = 251–257 | date = June 2015 | journal = Quantum Matter | publisher = American Scientific Publishers }} </ref> by slightly shifting the phase of its entry into the zone of interaction, while maintaining almost exactly the same amplitude and frequency. The values of the quantized amplitudes &ndash; and the corresponding energies of the quantized modes &ndash; are essentially independent of the strength of the alternating current supplied to the electromagnet, over a very large range. The higher the applied frequency, the larger the array of stable modes that become accessible to the pendulum (See Table 1).
