[[File:NøkkiBergen1.JPG|thumb|Fossegrim playing a harp in a waterfall under the statue to the violinist [[Ole Bull]] in [[Bergen]]]] In [[Scandinavian folklore]], the '''fossegrim''', also known simply as the '''grim''' ([[Norwegian language|Norwegian]]) or '''Strömkarlen''' ([[Swedish language|Swedish]]), is a water spirit or troll who plays the fiddle, especially the [[Hardanger fiddle]], and can be induced to teach the skill.
The fossegrim is related to the [[Neck (water spirit)|neck]] or nixie and is sometimes also called ''näcken'' in Sweden, but is associated with rivers (the Swedish name "Strömkarlen" means "The River Man") and particularly with waterfalls (''foss'' in Norwegian) and [[Watermill|mill race]]s.<ref name=Thorpe>[[Benjamin Thorpe]], ''Northern Mythology: comprising the principal popular traditions and superstitions of Scandinavia, north Germany, and the Netherlands'', 3 vols. London: Lumley, 1851&ndash;52, {{OCLC|656592812}}, Volume 2 ''Scandinavian Popular Traditions and Superstitions'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=TTMMAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA23&dq=Fossegrim p.&nbsp;23].</ref> He has been associated with the ''kvernknurr'', a mill spirit.<ref name="Mogk">[[Eugen Mogk]], ''Mythologie'', Grundriß der germanischen Philologie 1, Strasbourg: Trübner, 1891, {{OCLC|162976637}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=NxIWAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1038&dq=Fossegrim,+Wasser&hl=en&sa=X&ei=nMnbVJ-XGcbqoATN2ICwCQ&ved=0CGIQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=Fossegrim%2C%20Wasser&f=false p.&nbsp;1028] {{de icon}} equated them, but Reimund Kvideland and [[Henning Sehmsdorf]], ''Scandinavian Folk Belief and Legend'', Nordic Series 15, Minneapolis: University of Minnesota, 1988, {{ISBN|9780816615032}}, [https://books.google.com/books?id=_wTCSv2CGqUC&pg=PA422&dq=Fossegrim,+Kvernknurr&hl=en&sa=X&ei=3MvbVJP1F8fxoATV7oDYCQ&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAA#v=snippet&q=mill%20sprite&f=false p.&nbsp;248], distinguish the "mill sprite" as a mischievous creature who punishes grinding on Christian holy days.</ref>
The fossegrim is described as an exceptionally talented fiddler: the sounds of forest, wind and water play over his fiddle strings. The Swedish strömkarl's lay is said to have eleven variations, the final one being reserved for the night spirits because when it is played, "tables and benches, cup and can, gray-beards and grandmothers, blind and lame, even babes in the cradle" will begin to dance.<ref>[[Jacob Grimm]], ''[[Deutsche Mythologie|Teutonic Mythology]]'', 4th ed. tr. James Stallybrass, Volume 2, London: Bell, 1883, {{OCLC|457311367}}, pp.&nbsp;492&ndash;93.</ref> The fossegrim is said to be willing to teach away his skills in exchange for a food offering made on a Thursday evening and in secrecy: a white he-goat thrown with head turned away into a waterfall that flows northwards,<ref name=Thorpe/><ref name=Grimm>Jacob Grimm, ''Teutonic Mythology'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=fiAAAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA493&dq=Fossegrim+Grimm&hl=en&sa=X&ei=G67bVJTOI4G1ogTK2ICgCw&ved=0CCIQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Fossegrim%20Grimm&f=false p.&nbsp;493].</ref> or ''fenalår'' (smoked mutton) stolen from the neighbour's storage four Thursdays in a row. If there is not enough meat on the bone, he will only teach the supplicant how to tune the fiddle. If the offering is satisfactory, he will take the pupil's right hand and draw the fingers along the strings until they all bleed, after which he will be able to play so well that "the trees shall dance and torrents in their fall stand still".<ref name=Thorpe/><ref name=Grimm/> [[Jacob Grimm]] cites a variant in Johan Ödman's 18th-century ''Chorographia Bahusiensis'' according to which the strömkarl must be offered [[Redemption (theology)|redemption]] or he will merely break his instrument and weep bitterly.<ref name=Grimm/>
Famous fiddlers who were said to have learnt from the fossegrim include Torgeir Augundsson, known as [[Myllarguten]] (who denied it to [[Theodor Kjerulf]]) and [[Ole Bull]], whose statue in the centre of [[Bergen]] depicts a fossegrim playing his harp under the falling water; the sculptor, [[Stephan Sinding]] (1846&ndash;1922), intended it to symbolise his being inspired by Norwegian nature and folklore.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} The folklorist [[Rikard Berge]] said that he told the story to the fiddler [[Håvard Gibøen]] when they were both boys but that neither believed it.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}
